<div id="review_1910411785" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1910411785" />
    <a title="Jonfaith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2327886-jonfaith"><img alt="Jonfaith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1534772484p2/2327886.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1910411785?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonfaith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonfaith" href="/user/show/2327886-jonfaith">Jonfaith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2327886-jonfaith?shelf=poetshere">poetshere</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1910411785" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6086945505733652918"><b>Since they&apos;d never met before, they&apos;re sure<br/>that there&apos;d been nothing between them.<br/>But what&apos;s the word from the streets, staircases, hallways--<br/>perhaps they&apos;ve passed by each other a million times?</b><br/><br/>My recent bouts with verse have been belabored, not in terms of complexity or allusion but because, so often, the stanzas were heavy. The weight of history and personal affectation gave each phrase a heft. Imagine how disoriented I was when encountering Szymborska. This collection nearly bursts with a wi</span>
  <span id="freeText6086945505733652918" style="display:none"><b>Since they'd never met before, they're sure<br />that there'd been nothing between them.<br />But what's the word from the streets, staircases, hallways--<br />perhaps they've passed by each other a million times?</b><br /><br />My recent bouts with verse have been belabored, not in terms of complexity or allusion but because, so often, the stanzas were heavy. The weight of history and personal affectation gave each phrase a heft. Imagine how disoriented I was when encountering Szymborska. This collection nearly bursts with a wild-eyed wonder. There is a freshness to almost every observation. There is a youthful lightness which appears to almost float from one stanza to the next. <br /><br />It shouldn't be assumed then that this collection is childish, not without first accepting a subtle weary edge. My favorite line is "My faith is strong, blind and without foundation." That disconnect creates an opening, a fissure of sighs where wonder goes to molt. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6086945505733652918" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
