    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_252431933" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/252431933" />
    <a title="David Greco" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5086912-david-greco"><img alt="David Greco" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/252431933?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Greco" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Greco" href="/user/show/5086912-david-greco">David Greco</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer252431933" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10702851200061140051">Wow. I am not a big poetry reader but this absolutely blew me away. Don&apos;t be scared off her being a Polish Nobel Laureate. She is not some &quot;obscure European writer, full of hard consonants and solemn purposes&quot; as one NPR review noted. The poetry here is very accessible and her ability to take a really good poem and make it great with just a turn of a phrase or a simple line is breathtaking. It starts off with: <br/><br/>BRUEGHEL’S TWO MONKEYS<br/><br/>This is what I see in my dreams about final exams:<br/>two monkeys, c</span>
  <span id="freeText10702851200061140051" style="display:none">Wow. I am not a big poetry reader but this absolutely blew me away. Don't be scared off her being a Polish Nobel Laureate. She is not some "obscure European writer, full of hard consonants and solemn purposes" as one NPR review noted. The poetry here is very accessible and her ability to take a really good poem and make it great with just a turn of a phrase or a simple line is breathtaking. It starts off with: <br /><br />BRUEGHEL’S TWO MONKEYS<br /><br />This is what I see in my dreams about final exams:<br />two monkeys, chained to the floor, sit on the windowsill,<br />the sky behind them flutters,<br />the sea is taking its bath.<br /><br />The exam is History of Mankind.<br />I stammer and hedge.<br /><br />One monkey stares and listens with mocking disdain,<br />the other seems to be dreaming away–<br />but when it’s clear I don’t know what to say<br />he prompts me with a gentle<br />clinking of his chain.<br /><br />That last line did it for me and I was hooked. After so many good poems I had to stop marking which ones I liked as I would have marked the entire book. As she writes in "Under One Small Star", "Don't bear me ill will, speech, that I borrow weighty words,then labor heavily so that they may seem light." And in that she succeeds. In "Thank You Note", she captures the forgotten moments and people that make life normal. Instead of focusing on the high drama and passion of life, she reminds us that is the simple, rarely noticed things that we should be thankful for because:<br /><br />I understand<br />what love can’t.<br />and forgive<br />as love never would<br /><br />Elegant and beautiful. A must read even if you normally are not into poetry.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10702851200061140051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

