<div id="review_224909103" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/224909103" />
    <a title="Martin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6709840-martin"><img alt="Martin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1363799197p2/6709840.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/224909103?book_show_action=true">Oct 18, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Martin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Martin" href="/user/show/6709840-martin">Martin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer224909103" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10727278679577194639">I didn&apos;t review this at the time I added it as &apos;read&apos;, but it is definitely one of my all-time favorite books of poetry. So on the occasion of Szymborska&apos;s passing I thought I would pass this along.<br/><br/>The world lost one of the most beautiful voices in all of literature. Szymborska was Poland&apos;s foremost Poet Laureate (magnifying Czeslaw Milosz) but her humane vision was clear in any language (I read her in three). I think it only dawned on me recently how important her work was in my personal develo</span>
  <span id="freeText10727278679577194639" style="display:none">I didn't review this at the time I added it as 'read', but it is definitely one of my all-time favorite books of poetry. So on the occasion of Szymborska's passing I thought I would pass this along.<br /><br />The world lost one of the most beautiful voices in all of literature. Szymborska was Poland's foremost Poet Laureate (magnifying Czeslaw Milosz) but her humane vision was clear in any language (I read her in three). I think it only dawned on me recently how important her work was in my personal development. From ironic themes of 'otherness' to her influence on Kieslowski (my favorite filmmaker) it's obvious that I retain some unconscious ties to my mother tongue, though it's more a second language to me than a first. Her poems are remarkable for saying the most devastating thing in the warmest way. And she took to heart Shakespeare's admonishing view that "brevity is the soul of wit", producing a startlingly small body of work.<br /><br />Yet even in death she speaks eloquently of life:<br /><br />Śmierć tylko taka. Bólu więcej<br />miałeś trzymając różę w ręce<br />i większe czułeś przerażenie<br />widząc, że płatek spadł na ziemię.<br /><br /><br />Thank you Wisława, spoczywaj w pokoju.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10727278679577194639" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


