<span id="freeTextContainer8136534467681241446">This is my first Szymborska work but will not be my last. Thoroughly enjoyed the chronological set up of the book, showing the different collections released in her life. <br/><br/>Favorite poems included: Nothing Twice; Travel Elegy; Poetry Reading, Water; Landscape; Advertisement (reminded me a lot of the Rolling Stones’ Mother’s Little Helper); Birthday (very Silverstein / Seuss-like); True Love; Under One Small Star; A Large Number; The Terrorist, He’s Watching; In Praise of My Sister; The Onion; In P</span>
  <span id="freeText8136534467681241446" style="display:none">This is my first Szymborska work but will not be my last. Thoroughly enjoyed the chronological set up of the book, showing the different collections released in her life. <br /><br />Favorite poems included: Nothing Twice; Travel Elegy; Poetry Reading, Water; Landscape; Advertisement (reminded me a lot of the Rolling Stones’ Mother’s Little Helper); Birthday (very Silverstein / Seuss-like); True Love; Under One Small Star; A Large Number; The Terrorist, He’s Watching; In Praise of My Sister; The Onion; In Praise of Feeling Bad About Yourself; Pi; Hitler’s First Photograph; The Century’s Decline; Children of Our Age; Tortures; Funeral; The End and the Beginning; Hatred.<br /><br />“Everything’s mine but just on loan, / nothing for the memory to hold, / though mine as long as I look.” – p. 19, from Travel Elegy <br /><br />“War is punishment and peace is a reward. / Shameful dreams all come from Satan. / My soul is as plain as the stone of a plum.” – p. 38, from Landscape</span>
